   # SLIDE 20: Dysprosium Amplifies Sensitivity\
   # ============================================================\
   add_notes(prs.slides[19],\
   """The thermal spike model predicts N52SH (lower coercivity, 19 kOe) should be MORE vulnerable than N42EH (higher coercivity, 30 kOe). We observe the\
   OPPOSITE: N42EH degrades more (-0.252% vs -0.170%).\
\
   Resolution: Allstar Magnetics composition data confirms N42EH contains 1-2 wt% Dysprosium, while N52SH contains ZERO Dy.\
\
   Why Dy matters:\
   - Dy has a thermal neutron capture cross-section of 994 barns (very high)\
   - Dy accounts for 98% of the rare-earth neutron capture differential between the two grades\
   - In modern NdFeB manufacturing, Dy is added via grain boundary diffusion (GBD), which concentrates it precisely at grain boundaries\
   - Grain boundaries are the structurally weakest points; Dy neutron captures deposit energy directly where it matters most for coercivity\
\
   This is a novel and actionable finding: for radiation environments, prefer Dy-free NdFeB grades.\
\
   If asked about Tb (Terbium): Both grades contain Tb (2-4%), but Tb has only 23 barns (43x less effective than Dy per atom). The Tb contribution is\
   negligible compared to Dy.""")\
