   # SLIDE 22: SmCo Activation Problem\
   # ============================================================\
   add_notes(prs.slides[21],\
   """This slide is important context for why SmCo can't simply replace NdFeB in FFA magnets.\
\
   Co-60: Natural cobalt is 100% Co-59. Single neutron capture produces Co-60, which has a 5.27-year half-life and emits intense gamma rays (1.17 + 1.33\
   MeV). This is the same isotope used in industrial irradiators. In an FFA with thousands of SmCo magnets near the beamline, the Co-60 inventory would\
   create serious shielding and personnel safety challenges. Standard cooling times (weeks to months) are insufficient for a 5.27-year isotope.\
\
   Sm-149 burn-up: Sm-149 has an extraordinary 40,140 barn cross-section. It progressively transmutes, changing the material composition over time. The\
   daughter Sm-151 has a ~90-year half-life, creating a long-lived waste liability.\
\
   Brittleness: SmCo is ceramic-like. If an activated SmCo magnet fractures during handling or maintenance, it creates dispersible radioactive\
   contamination (loose activated particles). This is a serious RADCON concern.\
\
   CBETA precedent: Cornell-BNL's CBETA project specifically chose NdFeB over SmCo for their permanent magnet ERL, citing activation concerns.\
\
   Details in JLAB-TN-26-054 (our internal tech note on SmCo activation).\
\
   If asked "so SmCo is not an option at all?": For individual shielded magnets or test setups, SmCo is fine. For a large-scale FFA with thousands of\
   magnets requiring hands-on maintenance, the activation and handling risks are prohibitive.""")\
