   # SLIDE 25: Mitigation Strategies\
   # ============================================================\
   add_notes(prs.slides[24],\
   """Present these as options being considered, not recommendations. Each has significant drawbacks.\
\
   Grade selection: Dy-free NdFeB (like N52SH) shows 30% less degradation than N42EH. But this limits the available coercivity range. Other exotic\
   compositions exist but are expensive and unproven.\
\
   Local shielding: Borated polyethylene or other neutron absorbers around critical magnets. Adds mass and complexity to an already compact FFA geometry.\
\
   Design margin: Over-specify magnets so they can tolerate some degradation. Requires knowing the degradation rate, which is what Campaign 2+ aims to\
   provide.\
\
   Magic Fingers: Adjustable corrector wedges developed by N'Gotta at BNL for Halbach arrays. Can compensate for field quality changes in-situ. Open\
   questions about feasibility at the scale of a full FFA ring.\
\
   Periodic replacement: Operationally burdensome and expensive. Also requires predicting when replacement is needed.\
\
   Magnet sorting: Place the most radiation-resistant magnets at the highest-dose locations. Requires detailed dose mapping and increases procurement\
   complexity.\
\
   Electromagnetic FFA: Eliminates the radiation damage problem entirely by using conventional electromagnets instead of permanent magnets. However,\
   electromagnetic FFAs have not been demonstrated at energies relevant to the CEBAF upgrade, and the R&D required is substantial. This fundamentally\
   changes the FFA design concept.""")\
