   Right panel: Per-session Spearman correlations. 3 positive, 4 negative (no consistent sign). If gain drift were causing a real effect, we'd expect\
   consistent sign across all sessions.\
\
   Pooled result: rho = 0.146, p = 0.12. Not significant. The "cancels by construction" argument is empirically validated: because all 4 slots on a plate\
   are measured consecutively (median time gap: 102 seconds between first and last slot), any gain drift over the session affects all slots equally and\
   doesn't affect the differential.""")\
\
   # Slide 38: Literature Comparison\
   add_notes(prs.slides[37],\
   """Show if asked about how our results compare to prior work.\
\
   Key context: Prior deliberate irradiation studies typically used doses 100-1000x higher than ours (kGy to MGy range). Our study fills the low-dose,\
   real-accelerator regime that no one else has explored with this sample size and precision.\
\
   Important references if asked:\
   - Alderman (2002): Co-60 gamma null at 7 MGy, fast neutron 0.6% at 2.3e13 n/cm2 (ORNL). Supports our gamma-null finding.\
   - Miyahara (2010): 10 MeV neutrons, 0.6% at 1.1 kGy to 47.3% at 7.4 kGy. Overlaps our high-dose plates.\
   - Simos (2018): NdFeB/SmCo co-irradiation at Mrad-Grad doses, but only N=3 samples.\
   - Our study: N=30 tunnel plates, sub-percent detection at 7.6 sigma, real accelerator environment.\
\
   What makes us unique: co-located NdFeB/SmCo differential (gain-immune), sample size 10-100x larger than any prior study, and real accelerator exposure\
   rather than targeted irradiation.""")\
\
   # Slide 39: Blind Analysis Plan\
   add_notes(prs.slides[38],\
   """Show if asked about analyst bias or reproducibility.\
\
   Campaign 1 had five structural safeguards against bias:\
   1. Randomized slot assignments (material positions unknown during measurement)\
   2. Pre-registered analysis metric (Helmholtz % change, chosen before seeing data)\
   3. Automated pipeline (no manual data adjustment)\
   4. Multiple measurement systems (Helmholtz + Teslameter cross-check)\
   5. Lab controls (independent validation)\
\
   Campaign 2 adds a formal blind analysis:\
   - First run the standard (unblinded) analysis\
   - Then anonymize tunnel vs. lab plate identities\
   - Freeze the analysis pipeline code\
   - Run on anonymized data\
   - Lock results before unblinding\
   - Independent key-holder (not the analyst)\
\
   This directly addresses the concern that the analyst might unconsciously bias the analysis toward a positive result. If the blind analysis reproduces\
   the unblinded result, it's strong evidence against analyst bias.""")\
\
   # Slide 40: Spearman Explainer\
   add_notes(prs.slides[39],\
   """Show if asked "what is Spearman correlation?" or "why not use Pearson?"\
\
   TALKING POINTS FOR NON-STATISTICIANS:\
\
   Spearman rho is simply the Pearson correlation computed on RANKED data instead of raw data.\
\
   Step 1: Take your dose values (8 rem, 20 rem, ... 156,000 rem) and replace them with their ranks (1, 2, ... 30). Do the same for degradation values.\
\
   Step 2: Compute the ordinary Pearson correlation on the ranks.\
\
   Why ranks? Our dose data spans 4 orders of magnitude (8 to 156,000 rem) with extreme right skew (skewness = 2.1). A few high-dose linac plates dominate\
    any Pearson correlation on raw data. Ranking eliminates the influence of outliers and extreme values.\
\
   What Spearman tests: Does higher dose rank tend to correspond to higher (or lower) degradation rank? It detects monotonic trends without assuming the\
   relationship is linear and without assuming the data is normally distributed.\
\
   Panel 1 (left): Raw data on log scale. Hard to see any relationship.\
   Panel 2 (middle): Same data, rank-transformed. The positive trend is visible. The red line is a linear fit; its slope (0.46) equals the Spearman rho.\
   Panel 3 (right): The dose distribution histogram. Extreme right skew makes Pearson on raw data unreliable. Pearson assumes normality; Spearman does\
   not.\
\
   Our result: rho = 0.459 means there is a moderate positive monotonic relationship between neutron dose rank and degradation rank. p = 0.011 means there\
    is only a 1.1% probability of seeing this correlation by chance if no real relationship exists.""")\
