  The vendor curve you sent is for a generic NdFeB grade (likely N35 or similar, Hci ~12 kOe, max operating temp ~80C). Our magnets are high-coercivity\
  grades: N42EH (Hci = 30 kOe, rated to 190C) and N52SH (Hci = 19 kOe, rated to 140C). The energy barriers for domain relaxation scale strongly with\
  coercivity, so the vendor curve overstates aging for our materials by a large factor.\
\
  I ran a worst-case calculation assuming 45C for the full 12 months (which overstates things; 45C was a single outlier, typical tunnel temp is 30-35C). The\
  key insight is that our measurement design compares tunnel plates to lab plates, and both sets undergo the initial "knock-down" you described. The relevant\
   quantity is the 
\f3\i excess
\f0\i0  aging at tunnel temperature vs. lab temperature, not the absolute aging. That excess comes out to roughly 0.03% for our\
  grade-corrected NdFeB average, which is about 6x too small to explain the observed 0.201% tunnel-lab difference.\
\
  There's also a peer-reviewed framework for this. Haavisto and Paju (2009, IEEE Trans. Magn. 45(12), 5277-5280) showed that sintered NdFeB with high\
  coercivity is thermally stable below a critical temperature T_0. For Hci in the 25-30 kOe range, T_0 is approximately 120-150C. Below T_0, time-dependent\
  flux losses are negligible even on multi-decade timescales. At 45C, our grades are well below T_0. They also showed (Haavisto et al., 2014) that the total\
  flux loss after 30 years is approximately 2x the loss after 1 hour, a consequence of logarithmic time dependence. So even long exposures don't accumulate\
  much beyond the initial settling.\
