\f0\b0 \
\
  Pros:\
  - You get the probe-sample contact temperature 
\f3\i before
\f0\i0  the Helmholtz measurement rather than after. In a warming room, this is a 
\f3\i leading
\f0\i0  indicator rather\
  than trailing.\
  - No advantage over current order for the differential.\
\
  Cons:\
  - In a warming room, the Teslameter temperature now 
\f3\i underestimates
\f0\i0  the sample temp at Helmholtz time (opposite sign of the current bias). Neither order\
  gives you the probe temperature at the exact Helmholtz moment.\
  - Workflow is slower: Teslameter measurements take longer per sample (especially with multi-insertion), so the critical Helmholtz measurement happens later\
   in the session, when operator fatigue is higher and any interruption (power glitch, phone call) is more likely to have already occurred. Helmholtz first\
  gets the primary science measurement done while the operator is freshest.\
\
  
\f1\b Randomized
\f0\b0  
\f1\b order
\f0\b0 \
\
  This is actually the most interesting option, specifically for the 
\f1\b summer
\f0\b0  
\f1\b cross-calibration
\f0\b0  
\f1\b study
